### Describe the bug

The dotnet-monitor tool produces HTTP response bodies that have the shape of `ValidationProblemDetails` when bad request occurs; in fact, it instantiates this class, fills it out, and sends it back as a `BadRequestObjectResult`. The response body typically looks like `{\"status\":400,\"detail\":\"HTTP egress is not enabled.\"}`.

We have tests that validate that dotnet-monitor is producing the expected responses. For bad requests, it deserializes the response body to validate the appropriate error information is produced. Starting in .NET 8.0 Preview 2, deserialization of the response body using `JsonSerializer.DeserializeAsync<ValidationProblemDetails>` no longer fills out the object as expected. The `status` and `detail` values from the JSON end up in the `Extensions` property rather than the `Status` and `Detail` properties.

### Expected Behavior

When deserializing JSON content in the shape of a `application/problem+json` content type, the `ValidationProblemDetails` object should be filled in correctly.

### Steps To Reproduce

The Status and Details property assertions fail with ASP.NET Core 8.0 Preview 2 whereas they've worked on all prior versions.

```cs
string content = "{\"status\":400,\"detail\":\"HTTP egress is not enabled.\"}";
using MemoryStream stream = new();
using StreamWriter writer = new(stream);
writer.Write(content);
writer.Flush();
stream.Position = 0;

JsonSerializerOptions options = new();
options.Converters.Add(new JsonStringEnumConverter());

ValidationProblemDetails details = await JsonSerializer.DeserializeAsync<ValidationProblemDetails>(stream, options);
Assert.Equal(400, details.Status);
Assert.Equal("HTTP egress is not enabled.", details.Detail);
```

